. The user mentioned keeping tests under the source root, so I’ll need to consider the best structure for this without violating any class mapping rules.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test file structure**\\n\\nIt looks like there’s a guideline saying that each dynamic-access class should have its own dedicated Java test file, and top-level test classes need to be public. I guess creating a top-level Kotlin test might not be the best move. However, could a helper Kotlin type be treated as a top-level public class? Not sure if that class really counts as a test file, especially since it doesn't end with \\\"Test.\\\" I wonder if the rule really only applies to Java files.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Kotlin plugin needs**\\n\\nI see that support files are allowed inside the target, which is good. I'm wondering if I need to add the Kotlin plugin. Maybe the root plugin management has the Kotlin plugin? It seems like a good idea to inspect the settings to double-check. I'll need to figure this out to ensure everything works smoothly. Exploring these options is key!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_McmY2PGygTAqvJAcjLWD08ui|fc_07a6a49c334623cf016a2ac6ec3108819684c2832e927d813c", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.mockito/mockito-core/5.0.0/settings.gradle"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 775, "output": 1551, "cacheRead": 27648, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29974, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781188291166, "responseId": "resp_07a6a49c334623cf016a2ac6c3e2988196b2af9411aacbda3c"}}
