[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Kotlin test setup**\n\nI think I need to add a Kotlin test helper through the Gradle Kotlin plugin, but it seems there might be strict rules about Java test files. I could create a Kotlin source, but the dynamic-access class needs a dedicated Java test file under src/test/java. It's possible to compile a Kotlin helper class from Java, but I'm unsure if .kt files can go into src/test/java directly. The user mentioned keeping tests under the source root, so I’ll need to consider the best structure for this without violating any class mapping rules.\n\n**Evaluating test file structure**\n\nIt looks like there’s a guideline saying that each dynamic-access class should have its own dedicated Java test file, and top-level test classes need to be public. I guess creating a top-level Kotlin test might not be the best move. However, could a helper Kotlin type be treated as a top-level public class? Not sure if that class really counts as a test file, especially since it doesn't end with \"Test.\" I wonder if the rule really only applies to Java files.\n\n**Considering Kotlin plugin needs**\n\nI see that support files are allowed inside the target, which is good. I'm wondering if I need to add the Kotlin plugin. Maybe the root plugin management has the Kotlin plugin? It seems like a good idea to inspect the settings to double-check. I'll need to figure this out to ensure everything works smoothly. Exploring these options is key!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_07a6a49c334623cf016a2ac6c4a3548196bf789193e8d733b8\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqKsbs5n6MJvprEbB4Ks1k5vmiaTVL0thrU0kaTZWb0qRtHnghMvu_GxPlHaIGcFpMN2ZanECDeFCNlTmHZfx4pgbSWLteAUeA1gefs874brgULLajUjs3OyIrBf2quDt381hAFF1tqMEzjYl13PXb81Rjq6b2h2m3IuKglLDvBUTB2e_5xs9d3TtgE8WOYIXy51QRlkdOASMKr1DKxZptTRsRxHthWBabkDwJWiXDewQEDZIFDrvWD1jmPwsDfnKiPPYHRXlDPEnVUQh7vXXv